How Fusion Works and What It Produces
In fusion, two light nuclei, typically the hydrogen isotopes deuterium and =
tritium (D-T), merge to form a single heavier nucleus. The process releases=
 energy because the total mass of the resulting single nucleus is less than=
 the mass of the two original nuclei. The leftover mass becomes a tremendou=
s amount of energy in the form of neutrons, per Einstein=E2=80=99s famous f=
ormula: E=3Dmc2.
In the D-T fusion reaction, the neutron carries away most of the energy rel=
eased, approximately 14.1 MeV (million electron volts). These high-energy n=
eutrons can be used for various purposes, like generating heat for electric=
ity production or even for material testing.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99re familiar with fusion and largely think of it in terms of =
clean, abundant energy, here=E2=80=99s a little mental shift that=E2=80=99s=
 helpful in understanding what Fuse is doing:=C2=A0
High-energy neutrons are the product of D-T fusion reactions.=C2=A0
One application of those neutrons might be electricity production, but ther=
e are other valuable ways to use those neutrons.=C2=A0
Hold that thought.=C2=A0
Fusing two atoms together is hard, primarily because of electrostatic repul=
sion. Atomic nuclei are positively charged because they contain protons, an=
d repel each other similar to how magnets of like poles repel each other. T=
his, incidentally, is why light atoms make the easiest fusion fuels: fewer =
protons, less electrostatic repulsion.=C2=A0
Fusion needs a controlled environment of more than 100 million degrees Cels=
ius and as dense as the core of the Sun for long enough for the reaction to=
 ignite. These three parameters =E2=80=93 density, temperature, and confine=
ment time =E2=80=93 make up the =E2=80=9Ctriple product.=E2=80=9D
Higher Density means more fuel particles are available to collide and fuse.
Higher Temperature increases the likelihood that these collisions will have=
 enough energy to overcome the electrostatic repulsion between positively c=
harged nuclei.
Longer Confinement Time ensures that the energy and particles stay within t=
he plasma long enough for more fusion reactions to occur.
In order for a fusion reaction to reach ignition, or become self-sustaining=
, the triple product needs to reach a certain threshold, at least 1020 KeV =
s/m3. Different generators attempt to clear that bar by optimizing the trip=
le product variables in different ways.
Magnetic confinement fusion systems, like tokamaks and stellarators, strive=
 for confinement times on the order of seconds to minutes at high temperatu=
res but low densities. Inertial confinement fusion systems, like NIF, have =
confinement times measured in nanoseconds, but make up for lost time, as it=
 were, with higher temperatures and densities.
Fuse=E2=80=99s Generator of Choice: MagLIF
Fuse is pursuing MagLIF, or Magnetized Liner Inertial Fusion, which falls s=
omewhere in between magnetic confinement and inertial confinement on the sp=
ectrum of triple product optimization.=C2=A0
MagLIF uses a self-induced strong magnetic field =E2=80=93 created with a h=
igh electrical current as opposed to super strong magnets, like Commonwealt=
h Fusion Systems uses =E2=80=93 to confine and compress a preheated and mag=
netized fuel, typically deuterium-tritium, within a metallic liner. The lin=
er is then rapidly imploded using a powerful electrical current, further co=
mpressing and heating the fuel to fusion conditions.
By borrowing pieces from each approach, eliminating inefficiencies, and avo=
iding extremes, MagLIF has the potential to be 10x more efficient and less =
than 10% the cost and size of laser-driven inertial confinement generators =
like NIF. That=E2=80=99s a bold statement that has been peer-reviewed in Fu=
se=E2=80=99s publication in the tier-1 scientific journal,  [ https://subst=
ack.com/redirect/b01dcc02-b4f1-497c-8cf6-e727bb34beaf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3Qif=
Q.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]Vacuum [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/b01dcc02-b4f1-497c-8cf6-e727bb34beaf?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Compared to a tokamak like the m=
ultinational ITER [ https://substack.com/redirect/880eb7d3-2835-45db-a310-7=
3c9b32e0f80?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkR=
NpU ] project, MagLIF can be less than 5% of the cost.=C2=A0
The Z Machine itself is not a MagLIF fusion generator. It=E2=80=99s a pulse=
d power generator that can run MagLIF experiments.
A pulsed power generator charges capacitors =E2=80=93 think of them like ba=
tteries =E2=80=93 over a relatively long period of time and then releases t=
he stored energy very quickly in the form of a high-power pulse. Those puls=
es shoot a tremendous amount of current =E2=80=93 Z does 26 megaamps (MA) =
=E2=80=93 at the target in a very short amount of time.=C2=A0
In MagLIF experiments on the Z Machine, the target is a cylindrical metal l=
iner containing a preheated and magnetized deuterium-tritium fuel. In this =
process:=C2=A0
The fuel is preheated and magnetized.
The electrical current from the Z Machine is applied to the outer surface o=
f the liner.
This current generates a strong magnetic field that rapidly compresses the =
liner inward.
The compression of the liner further heats and compresses the fuel inside, =
creating conditions suitable for fusion reactions.
Pulsed-power generators are the critical component of MagLIF generators, an=
d capacitors are the critical component of pulsed-power generators.=C2=A0
There are other important components, but I=E2=80=99ve thrown a lot at you =
already, and that=E2=80=99s the simplest way to think about the pulsed powe=
r generators Fuse is building.
The performance of pulsed-power generators, and therefore MagLIF generators=
, is largely determined by the capabilities of capacitors used, along a few=
 dimensions:
Energy density: Amount of energy that can be stored in a given volume of ca=
pacitor.
Voltage rating: Max voltage that the capacitor can withstand without breaki=
ng down.
Discharge rate: Speed at which the capacitor can release its stored energy.
Repetition rate: How quickly the capacitor can be recharged for the next pu=
lse.
Roughly =E2=80=93 and again, there are a number of other factors, but rough=
ly =E2=80=93 as capacitors improve, MagLIF generators are more likely to ac=
hieve Q>1, or breakeven, to get more energy out of the fusion reaction than=
 is put into it, and then Qcommercial>1, or commercial breakeven, when it c=
an make more money from selling power than it costs to produce it.=C2=A0=C2=
=A0
Q, the ratio of energy output to energy input, is related to the triple pro=
duct, but it=E2=80=99s not the same thing as the triple product.=C2=A0
You can achieve a super high triple product without achieving Q>1 by dumpin=
g a ton of energy into the process, but you cannot achieve Q>1 without a tr=
iple product greater than 1020 KeV s/m3.=C2=A0
Achieving that triple product is necessary for self-sustaining fusion, but =
it=E2=80=99s not sufficient. If you=E2=80=99re willing to pour more energy =
into a process than you get out =E2=80=93 say, because you want to run test=
s to ensure that America=E2=80=99s nuclear stockpile still works =E2=80=93 =
you can use fusion to produce radiation before you can achieve Q>1, or Q> w=
hatever you=E2=80=99d need to profitably produce electricity. Roughly, the =
higher your triple product, the more radiation you can produce.
Radiation Can Be Good, Actually
In the public consciousness, radiation is a dirty word. It brings to mind C=
hernobyl and radiation poisoning. But radiation is simply the emission of e=
nergy as electromagnetic waves or particles.=C2=A0
Neutrons are radiation in the form of particles, and X-rays and gamma rays =
are radiation in the form of high-energy electromagnetic waves. Too much of=
 the wrong types of radiation in our bodies is bad, but radiation powers th=
e world. The sun=E2=80=99s rays, for example, are radiation in the form of =
visible light, ultraviolet light, and infrared radiation.=C2=A0
Radiation is energy. Properly harnessed, radiation is good and valuable. An=
d controlled fusion can produce properly harnessed radiation, which many cu=
stomers are willing to buy.=C2=A0
This is why Fuse is pursuing MagLIF, starting by building modern pulsed-pow=
er generators. The MagLIF path can generate revenue at high margins by prod=
