Modernizing the Nuclear Arsenal=C2=A0
On the way to fusion power, Fuse plans to help America modernize and mainta=
in its nuclear arsenal in order to deter the threat of nuclear war in the f=
ace of rising tensions with nuclear adversaries.=C2=A0
In March, Sandia National Labs, on behalf of the NNSA, issued a Request for=
 Information (RFI) for a public-private partnership to build the next Z Mac=
hine, a billion-dollar-scale project inspired by the NASA COTS program that=
 launched SpaceX.=C2=A0
In April, Fuse entered into a five-year Cooperative Research and Developmen=
t Agreement (CRADA) with Sandia, which operates under the NNSA, under which=
 they share research and development on Next Generation Pulsed Power.=C2=A0
Nuclear safety is a large and growing priority for the US government as the=
 nuclear threat from our main adversaries strengthens. Both Russia and Chin=
a are modernizing their nuclear arsenals. While Russia, like the US, is mod=
ernizing its delivery capabilities, China is working on dramatically expand=
ing its nuclear arsenal [ https://substack.com/redirect/084ae91a-5f81-46b8-=
8c1b-5e4d163baeda?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6=
m8ExkRNpU ], from 500 warheads today to a projected 1,500 by 2035. While Ch=
atGPT certainly isn=E2=80=99t authoritative, this table comparing the three=
 superpowers=E2=80=99 nuclear plans is directionally useful:=C2=A0
To state the obvious, nuclear war with China or Russia would be catastrophi=
c. Nuclear deterrence is a complex and multifaceted topic =E2=80=93 it take=
s diplomacy, communication, agreements, confidence-building measures, weapo=
ns defense systems, and more =E2=80=93 there=E2=80=99s no substitute for ma=
intaining a capabilities advantage.=C2=A0
During the Cold War, President Raegan advocated for =E2=80=9Cpeace through =
strength,=E2=80=9D a modern expression of an old military principle advocat=
ed by Thucydides, Machiavelli, and Teddy Roosevelt, among others. Simply pu=
t, the best way to prevent another country from attacking America with nucl=
ear weapons is to make it clear that doing so would mean even more catastro=
phic consequences for their country.=C2=A0=C2=A0
America boasts the world=E2=80=99s largest nuclear arsenal, but most of our=
 nuclear weapons were built between the 1940s and the 1980s. The youngest a=
re forty years old.=C2=A0
Given the rising threat, the DoD is undergoing the largest modernization ef=
fort in the country=E2=80=99s history. As the Air Force=E2=80=99s Nuclear W=
eapons Center wrote in a DoD proposal:
The Department of Defense and the Air Force are in the middle of an unprece=
dented recapitalization of the ENTIRE nuclear triad to include the weapons =
themselves. Since the triad was created, this has never occurred in our his=
tory. This investment of over $1 trillion is budgeted, funded, and in build=
, above all other competing requirements and Defense needs, because it is n=
ecessary as the most important global deterrent in our arsenal to counter t=
hose who wish to dominate the United States and undo our freedoms.
The DoD is putting its money where its mouth is. According to the Congressi=
onal Budget Office [ https://substack.com/redirect/cc0a2a64-918a-40a6-8be1-=
