>Hold that thought.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Fusing two atoms together is=
 hard, primarily because of electrostatic repulsion. Atomic nuclei are posi=
tively charged because they contain protons, and repel each other similar t=
o how magnets of like poles repel each other. This, incidentally, is why li=
ght atoms make the easiest fusion fuels: fewer protons, less electrostatic =
repulsion.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Fusion needs a controlled envir=
onment of more than 100 million degrees Celsius and as dense as the core of=
 the Sun for long enough for the reaction to ignite. These three parameters=
 &#8211; density, temperature, and confinement time &#8211; make up the </s=
pan><strong>&#8220;triple product.&#8221;</strong></p><ul style=3D"margin-t=
op: 0; padding: 0;"><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: =
bullet;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4p=
x;"><strong>Higher Density</strong><span> means more fuel particles are ava=
ilable to collide and fuse.</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32p=
x; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: =
rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bott=
om: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Higher Temperature </strong><span>increa=
ses the likelihood that these collisions will have enough energy to overcom=
e the electrostatic repulsion between positively charged nuclei.</span></p>=
</li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 32px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p sty=
le=3D"box-sizing: border-box; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line=
-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Lon=
ger Confinement Time </strong><span>ensures that the energy and particles s=
tay within the plasma long enough for more fusion reactions to occur.</span=
></p></li></ul><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In order for a fusion reaction to re=
ach </span><strong>ignition</strong><span>, or become self-sustaining, the =
triple product needs to reach a certain threshold, at least </span><strong>=
<span>10</span><sup>20</sup><span> KeV s/m</span><sup>3</sup></strong><span=
>. Different generators attempt to clear that bar by optimizing the triple =
product variables in different ways.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 5=
5, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Ma=
gnetic confinement fusion systems</strong><span>, like tokamaks and stellar=
ators, strive for confinement times on the order of seconds to minutes at h=
igh temperatures but low densities. </span><strong>Inertial confinement fus=
ion systems</strong><span>, like NIF, have confinement times measured in na=
noseconds, but make up for lost time, as it were, with higher temperatures =
and densities.</span></p><h4 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-=
