: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>In a typical fission =
reaction, the goal is to set off a chain reaction. Plant operators insert f=
uel rods containing fissile material &#8211; typically uranium-235 or pluto=
nium-239 &#8211; into the reactor core and then activate a neutron source &=
#8211; like polonium-beryllium &#8211; to begin the process. The starter ne=
utrons hit the uranium atom, splitting it into two smaller atoms and a neut=
ron, which flies off and hits another uranium atom, which splits and releas=
es a neutron which hits another uranium atom, and so on. This is called </s=
pan><strong>going critical</strong><span>.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb=
(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">In t=
hese reactions, the neutron source is just a kickstarter &#8211; it does it=
s job, and then the chain reaction takes over.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: =
rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">B=
ut what if you had a way to consistently produce high-energy neutrons?&#160=
;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Fuse will. Its scheme is </span><strong>subcri=
tical</strong><span> by nature because it relies on the fusion reaction to =
continue producing neutrons, and therefore has none of the criticality conc=
erns associated with traditional nuclear fission reactors.</span></p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;"><span>In a hybrid fusion-fission reactor, like Apeiron, the D-T=
 fusion reaction in the core releases high-energy neutrons and large amount=
s of energy. Those neutrons fire off and hit a fission blanket surrounding =
the core, typically made of heavy atoms like uranium and, importantly, </sp=
an><strong>nuclear waste such as spent fuel from traditional reactors</stro=
ng><span>.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 1=
6px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">The blanket captures the high-=
energy neutrons, which can induce fission, generating energy, and transmute=
 long-lived radioactive isotopes into shorter-lived and more stable ones, r=
educing the long-term radiotoxicity and volume of nuclear waste.&#160;</p><=
