e: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>The process produc=
es power and reduces nuclear waste, both of which are valuable.&#160;</stro=
ng></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26=
px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>The US currently has a </span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/1c1da1fa-f68b-48b8-a956-8587c06aaa76?j=3DeyJ1Ijo=
iOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color=
: rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">$40 billion Nuclear Waste F=
und</a><span>, funded by a tax on electricity, to build a depository for nu=
clear waste. It&#8217;s a political quagmire &#8211; </span><a href=3D"http=
s://substack.com/redirect/14063adb-64ff-44f8-a30c-dd8b8d8f9fa0?j=3DeyJ1Ijoi=
OXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color:=
 rgb(54, 55, 55); text-decoration: underline;">look up Yucca Mountain</a><s=
pan> &#8211; and as a result, nuclear waste remains an unresolved and overb=
lown impediment to nuclear&#8217;s growth.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"colo=
r: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;=
"><span>Turning that waste into power would be a win for everyone. And Sand=
ia found that the numbers pencil out &#8211; 20MW, or 10</span><sup>19</sup=
><span> 14.1 MeV neutrons, of fusion output produces &#8220;Actinide blanke=
t output&#8221; of 3,000 MWth (megawatts thermal, or heat energy). At a ~30=
% conversion to electrical, 20MW of fusion output could drive a 1 gigawatt =
output. And because the reaction remains subcritical &#8211; it needs the f=
usion reaction to continue &#8211; there&#8217;s an easier regulatory path =
with the onerous Nuclear Regulatory Commission (NRC).&#160;</span></p><p st=
yle=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: =
0 0 20px 0;">To be sure, Fuse&#8217;s goal is to produce pure fusion energy=
 &#8211; to put an APEIRON fusion generator in every city in the world. By =
the time it builds a hybrid fusion-fission plant and produces electrons, th=
at&#8217;s just an engineering challenge.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(5=
4, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">It wil=
l need materials that can handle higher-density currents, better transmissi=
on lines, and more efficient and longer-lasting capacitors.&#160;</p><p sty=
le=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0=
 0 20px 0;">If your capacitor can only survive a million shots, and you nee=
d to replace it every year, your fusion plant may not be profitable despite=
 a high Q. &#8220;These are numbers a lot of fusion companies don&#8217;t t=
alk about,&#8221; JC told me. But if it can survive 9 or 10 million shots, =
the plant starts to look a lot more profitable.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color:=
 rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">=
<span>What drew JC and the team to MagLIF is that </span><strong>these aren=
&#8217;t science challenges, but engineering ones.</strong><span> They need=
 to figure out how to get shots fired efficiently, repetitively, and cheapl=
y, and the whole business is structured to generate revenue while simultane=
ously iterating away the engineering challenges.&#160;</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">The goal is to find markets that support both near-term revenue a=
nd the opportunity to improve the engineering on the path to fusion.&#160;<=
/p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-appearance: optimi=
zelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance: opt=
imizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optimizel=
egibility; color: rgb(54, 55, 55); font-family: 'SF Pro Display', -apple-sy=
